The paper discusses the limitations of interval probability representation in capturing epistemological independence. This topic is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), information theory (cs.IT), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper's focus on probability and independence suggests that it is more likely to belong to cs.AI and cs.LG, but the discussion of ontological interpretation could also make it relevant to cs.IT, cs.DS, and cs.SI.
